Recognition of proper nouns in Japanese text has been studied as a part of the more general problem of morphological analysis in Japanese text processing. It has also been studied in the framework of Japanese information extraction in recent years. Our approach to the Multi-lingual Evaluation Task (MET) for Japanese text is to consider the given task as a morphological analysis problem in Japanese. Our morphological analyzer, Amorph, has done all the necessary work for the recognition and classification of proper names, numerical and temporal expressions, i.e. Named Entity (NE) items in the Japanese text. Amorph recognizes NE items in two stages: dictionary lookup and rule application. First, it uses several kinds of dictionaries to segment and tag Japanese character strings. Second, based on the information resulting from the dictionary lookup stage, a set of rules is applied to the segmented strings in order to identify NE items. When a segment is found to be an NE item, this information is added to the segment and it is used to generate the final output.
We propose to incorporate geometric constraints in a 3-D stereo reconstruction scheme to improve accuracy in cases where image information alone is insufficient for 3-D shape recovery. Our approach involves iteratively deforming a 3-D surface mesh to minimize an objective function. By combining anisotropic meshing with a non-quadratic regularization approach, we achieve satisfactory reconstruction results with minimal triangulations. Local addition of structural or numerical constraints through a constrained optimization scheme enhances reconstruction and ensures consistency with prior knowledge of object shape. The descriptive and modeling capabilities of differential features serve as effective constraints for 3-D reconstruction.
This work proposes a new research direction to address the lack of structures in traditional n-gram models. It is based on a weakly supervised dependency parser that can model speech syntax without relying on any annotated training corpus. Labeled data is replaced by a few hand-crafted rules that encode basic syntactic knowledge. Bayesian inference then samples the rules, disambiguating and combining them to create complex tree structures that maximize a discriminative model's posterior on a target unlabeled corpus. This posterior encodes sparse selectional preferences between a head word and its dependents. The model is evaluated on English and Czech newspaper texts, and is then validated on French broadcast news transcriptions.
"Listen-Communicate-Show (LCS) is a new paradigm for human interaction with data sources. LCS integrates a spoken language understanding system with intelligent mobile agents that mediate between users and information sources. An application of this approach called LCS-Marine has been built and will be demonstrated. Using LCS-Marine, tactical personnel can converse with their logistics system to place a supply or information request. The request is passed to a mobile, intelligent agent for execution at the appropriate database. Requestors can also instruct the system to notify them when the status of a request changes or when a request is complete. This capability has been demonstrated in several field exercises with the Marines and is currently being developed for applications in new domains."
A domain independent model is proposed for the automated interpretation of nominal compounds in English. This model aims to explain the productive rules of interpretation based on the morpho-syntactic and semantic characteristics of the nominal constituents. The model extensively utilizes Pustejovsky's principles regarding the predicative information associated with nominals. It emphasizes the importance of distinguishing between generalizable semantic principles and domain-specific semantic information. The model's application to the interpretation of compounds in real texts is discussed, highlighting the need for complementary semantic information retrieval.
We introduce a novel method for detecting interest points using histogram information. Our detectors utilize histogram-based representations to identify image regions with unique distributions in the surrounding area. These detectors are capable of capturing large-scale structures and distinctive textured patterns, exhibiting robustness to rotation, illumination variations, and blur. Experimental findings indicate that the histogram-based interest point detectors excel in matching textured scenes amidst blur and illumination alterations in terms of repeatability and distinctiveness. Furthermore, we present an expansion of our approach to space-time interest point detection for action classification.
Plume is a restricted domain parser developed at Carnegie-Mellon University. Plume's parsing approach focuses on semantic caseframe instantiation, which allows for efficient processing of grammatical input and robust handling of ungrammatical input. This paper provides an overview of Plume's current state and discusses plans to improve its capabilities in dealing with passives, relative clauses, and interrogatives in a more comprehensive manner.
In this paper, we introduce a parser for German. The parser incorporates smoothing and suffix analysis to achieve a labelled bracket F-score of 76.2, surpassing previous results on the NEGRA corpus. The model demonstrates high accuracy. The inclusion of smoothing in an unlexicalized parser allows for a more in-depth examination of the connection between smoothing and parsing outcomes.
This paper presents an unsupervised learning approach to disambiguate various relations between named entities using lexical and syntactic features from the contexts. The approach involves calculating eigenvectors of an adjacency graph's Laplacian to recover a submanifold of data from a high dimensionality space and then performing cluster number estimation on the eigenvectors. Experimental results on ACE corpora demonstrate that this spectral clustering-based approach outperforms other clustering methods.
This paper proposes a generic mathematical formalism for the combination of various structures: strings, trees, dags, graphs, and products of them. The polarization of the objects of the elementary structures controls the saturation of the final structure. This formalism is both elementary and powerful enough to strongly simulate many grammar formalisms, such as rewriting systems, dependency grammars, TAG, HPSG, and LFG.
A mixed-signal paradigm is presented for high-resolution parallel inner-product computation in very high dimensions, suitable for efficient implementation of kernels in image processing. The core of the architecture is a high-density, low-power analog array performing binary-binary partial matrix-vector multiplication. Full digital resolution is maintained even with low-resolution analog-to-digital conversion, owing to random statistics in the analog summation of binary products. A random modulation scheme produces near-Bernoulli statistics even for highly correlated inputs. The approach is validated with real image data and experimental results from a CID/DRAM analog array prototype in 0.5 cents m CMOS.
In this paper, we focus on the projective unifocal, bifocal, and trifocal tensors in the affine case. We explore how these tensors are related to the registered tensors from previous studies. This allows us to establish an affine specialization of existing projective relationships that connect points and lines across two or three views. For affine cameras, we provide necessary and sufficient constraints on the components of the trifocal tensor, along with a straightforward geometric interpretation. Additionally, we demonstrate how to estimate the tensors from point correspondences using factorization and discuss the estimation from line correspondences.
This paper presents an algorithm for selecting an appropriate classifier word for a noun in the Thai language. There is often fluctuation in the choice of classifier for a concrete noun, both within the speech community and among individual speakers. A default rule is used to assign a classifier to each noun since there is no exact rule for classifier selection. The registration of classifiers is limited to unit classifiers due to the open nature of other types based on representation meaning. A corpus-based method, involving Biber, Nagao, and Smadja, generates Noun Classifier Associations (NCA) to address issues in classifier assignment and semantic construction of noun phrases. The NCA is statistically created from a large corpus and adjusted based on concept hierarchy constraints and frequency of occurrences.
The perception of transparent objects from images is known to be a challenging problem in vision. Transparent objects in a scene are difficult to detect from a single image. This paper explores the behavior of transparent objects when observed by a moving observer. Features seen through transparent objects behave differently from those rigidly attached to the scene. A novel model-based approach is presented to recover the shapes and poses of transparent objects based on known motion. These objects can be complex, consisting of multiple layers with varying refractive indices. The practical feasibility of the algorithm is verified through simulations and applied to real scenes, achieving high accuracy in recovering the shapes of transparent objects.
We propose a novel probabilistic framework for learning visual models of 3D object categories by combining appearance information and geometric constraints. Objects are represented as a coherent ensemble of parts that are consistent under 3D viewpoint transformations. Each part is a collection of salient image features. A generative framework is used for learning a model that captures the relative position of parts within each of the discretized viewpoints. Contrary to most of the existing mixture of viewpoints models, our model establishes explicit correspondences of parts across different viewpoints of the object class. Given a new image, detection and classification are achieved by determining the position and viewpoint of the model that maximize recognition scores of the candidate objects. Our approach is among the first to propose a generative probabilistic framework for 3D object categorization. We test our algorithm on the detection task and the viewpoint classification task by using the "car" category from both the Savarese et al. 2007 and PASCAL VOC 2006 datasets. We show promising results in both the detection and viewpoint classification tasks on these two challenging datasets.
We utilized ambiguity packing and stochastic disambiguation techniques for Lexical-Functional Grammars (LFG) in the context of sentence condensation. Our system comprises a linguistic parser/generator for LFG, a transfer component for parse reduction on packed parse forests, and a maximum-entropy model for stochastic output selection. We also recommend the use of standard parser evaluation methods to automatically evaluate the summarization quality of sentence condensation systems. An experimental assessment shows a strong correlation between automatic parse-based evaluation and manual evaluation of generated strings. The overall summarization quality of our system is excellent, with the system output guaranteed to be grammatically correct due to the use of a constraint-based parser/generator.
The robust principal component analysis problem, also known as robust PCA, is a common problem in machine learning applications. The goal is to decompose the data matrix into a low-rank part and a sparse residual. Current approaches focus on the low-rank plus sparse structure, but in many cases, additional side information about row and/or column entities is available. This paper explores robust PCA with side information, leveraging both prior structure and entity features for recovery. A convex problem is proposed to incorporate side information, demonstrating that the low-rank matrix can be accurately recovered under certain conditions. This method allows for the recovery of low-rank matrices that standard robust PCA cannot recover. The results support the effectiveness of features in robust PCA. Synthetic experiments and a real application in noisy image classification show that this method improves performance by utilizing side information.
This paper discusses the use of demonstrative expressions in English. It explores the implications for discourse processing algorithms. The distribution of demonstrative forms and functions is genre dependent. This research is part of a larger study on anaphoric expressions, with the results being integrated into a natural language generation system.
In the study of expressive speech communication, the emotion perceived by the listener is considered to be a good approximation of the intended emotion conveyed by the speaker. This paper examines the validity of this assumption by comparing the discrepancies between assessments made by naive listeners and the speakers who provided the data. The analysis is based on the hypothesis that individuals are better at decoding their own emotions, leading to self-assessments being closer to the intended emotions. Using the IEMOCAP database, emotional assessments categorized as discrete and continuous, evaluated by both actors and naive listeners, are compared. The results show a mismatch between the expression and perception of emotion, with speakers in the database assigning their own emotions to more specific emotional categories, resulting in more extreme values in the activation-valence space.
The problem of blind separation of underdetermined instantaneous mixtures of independent signals is addressed through a method relying on nonstationarity of the original signals. The signals are assumed to be piecewise stationary with varying variances in different epochs. In comparison with previous works, in this paper it is assumed that the signals are not i.i.d. in each epoch, but obey a first-order autoregressive model. This model was shown to be more appropriate for blind separation of natural speech signals. A separation method is proposed that is nearly statistically efficient, approaching the corresponding Cramér-Rao lower bound, if the separated signals obey the assumed model. In the case of natural speech signals, the method is shown to have separation accuracy better than the state-of-the-art methods.
This paper proposes the use of a convolution kernel over parse trees to model syntactic structure information for relation extraction. The study shows that syntactic structure features embedded in a parse tree are highly effective for relation extraction and can be well captured by the convolution tree kernel. Evaluation on the ACE 2003 corpus indicates that the convolution kernel over parse trees can achieve comparable performance with the previously best-reported feature-based methods on the 24 ACE relation subtypes. It also demonstrates that this method significantly outperforms the previous two dependency tree kernels on the 5 ACE relation major types.
This paper presents the results of automatically inducing a Combinatory Categorial Grammar (CCG) lexicon from a Turkish dependency treebank. Turkish is an agglutinating free word order language, which poses a challenge for language theories. The study explores methods to create a concise lexicon consistent with CCG principles from a smaller treebank compared to Penn WSJ.
Sentence extraction as an approach to summarization has been shown to work in documents of certain genres. However, due to the conversational nature of email communication, where utterances are made in relation to one made previously, sentence extraction may not capture the necessary segments of dialogue that would make a summary coherent. In this paper, the focus is on the detection of question-answer pairs in an email conversation for the task of email summarization. Various features based on the structure of email-threads can be used to improve upon lexical similarity of discourse segments for question-answer pairing.
In this paper, we focus on object detection with a limited number of training examples. We demonstrate how to integrate a basic prior on the distribution of natural images into support vector machines (SVMs). SVMs are known for their resistance to overfitting, but a small number of training examples may not accurately represent the class structure. As a result, the detectors produced may not be robust and heavily rely on the selection of training examples. By incorporating the prior on natural images, we ensure that the separating hyperplane not only provides a wide margin but also has a low probability of containing natural images (the background) in the positive half space. Our experiments on real datasets indicate that the resulting detector is more resilient to the choice of training examples and significantly enhances both linear and kernel SVM performance when trained on 10 positive and 10 negative examples.
The study of clustering focuses on a challenging goal. Developing a unified framework for reasoning about it has proven difficult. There are diverse approaches to clustering in the research community. A formal perspective on the challenge of unification is presented through an impossibility theorem, which shows that satisfying three simple properties with a clustering function is not possible. Trade-offs are inevitable in well-known clustering techniques like single-linkage, sum-of-pairs, k-means, and k-median.
We investigate event-based extractive multi-document summarization approaches. Events are defined as event terms and associated event elements. Important contents are identified based on the frequency of events with the independent approach. Using the relevant approach, important contents are identified using the PageRank algorithm on the event map constructed from documents. Experimental results show promising outcomes.
We present a scanning method that recovers dense sub-pixel camera-projector correspondence without requiring any photometric calibration or preliminary knowledge of their relative geometry. Subpixel accuracy is achieved by considering several zero-crossings defined by the difference between pairs of unstructured patterns. We use gray-level band-pass white noise patterns that increase robustness to indirect lighting and scene discontinuities. Simulated and experimental results show that our method recovers scene geometry with high subpixel precision and can handle many challenges of active reconstruction systems. We compare our results to state-of-the-art methods such as micro phase shifting and modulated phase shifting.
This paper describes a novel system for acquiring adjectival subcategorization frames and associated frequency information from English corpus data. The system incorporates a decision-tree classifier for various types of subcategorization frames which tests for the presence of grammatical relations in the output of a statistical parser. It uses a pattern-matching language to classify grammatical relations into frames hierarchically in a way that mirrors inheritance-based lexica. The experiments show that the system is able to detect subcategorization frame types with a precision of 70% and a recall rate of 66%. Additionally, a new tool for linguistic annotation of subcategorization frames in corpus data is introduced, which can significantly simplify the process of obtaining training and test data for subcategorization acquisition.
Machine transliteration and back-transliteration are essential in multilingual speech and language applications. A new framework for direct orthographical mapping (DOM) between two languages is presented in this paper. The framework includes a joint source-channel transliteration model, also referred to as n-gram transliteration model (n-gram TM), to depict the transliteration process. The effectiveness of these methods is assessed through experiments on English/Chinese and English/Japanese language pairs, demonstrating a notable enhancement in transliteration accuracy while streamlining system development efforts.
A bio-inspired model for an analog programmable array processor (APAP) has been developed based on studies on the vertebrate retina. This model enables the realization of complex programmable spatio-temporal dynamics in VLSI. It mimics image processing in the visual pathway, offering a potential solution for early vision applications in standard technologies. A prototype chip has been fabricated using a 0.5 µm standard CMOS process. The computing power per area and power consumption of this chip are among the highest reported for a single chip. The paper discusses design challenges, trade-offs, and presents some experimental results.
Determiners play a crucial role in conveying the meaning of an utterance. Determiners have often been overlooked, possibly because the focus was on understanding the overall meaning of a sentence, even if not precisely. Another issue with determiners is their inherent ambiguity. In this paper, we suggest a logical formalism that can represent determiners without imposing a specific interpretation when their meaning is uncertain.
We investigate the verbal and nonverbal means for grounding and propose a design for embodied conversational agents that relies on both kinds of signals to establish common ground in human-computer interaction. We analyzed eye gaze, head nods, and attentional focus in the context of a direction-giving task. The distribution of nonverbal behaviors differed depending on the type of dialogue move being grounded, and the overall pattern reflected a monitoring of lack of negative feedback. Based on these results, we present an ECA that uses verbal and nonverbal grounding acts to update dialogue state.
Sentence boundary detection in speech is important for enriching speech recognition output. In previous work, hidden Markov model (HMM) and maximum entropy (Maxent) classifiers have been developed to integrate textual and prosodic knowledge sources for detecting sentence boundaries. In this paper, the use of a conditional random field (CRF) for this task is evaluated and results are compared with prior work. The evaluation is conducted across two corpora - conversational telephone speech and broadcast news speech - on both human transcriptions and speech recognition output. The CRF model generally yields a lower error rate than the HMM and Maxent models on the NIST sentence boundary detection task in speech. It is interesting to note that the best results are achieved by three-way voting among the classifiers, likely due to each model having different strengths and weaknesses for modeling the knowledge sources.
We propose a novel approach to associate objects across multiple PTZ cameras for camera handoff in wide-area surveillance scenarios. Our approach involves the slave camera passively following the target (loosely registered with the master) and bootstrapping itself from its own incoming imagery. This method effectively overcomes limitations of previous approaches that relied on geometric, appearance, or correlation-based information. We also introduce a novel Multiple Instance Learning (MIL) formulation based on logistic softmax function of covariance-based region features within a MAP estimation framework. Our approach is demonstrated with multiple PTZ camera sequences in outdoor surveillance settings and compared with state-of-the-art approaches.
This paper addresses a specialized regression problem related to obtaining sampling probabilities for records in databases. The objective is to sample a small set of records for efficient and accurate evaluation of aggregate queries. The proposed solution is principled and provable, requiring no parameters or data insights. Unlike traditional regression problems, the loss is inversely proportional to the regressed-to values. Additionally, a cost zero solution is always possible unless restricted by hard budget constraints. A unique form of regularization is also necessary. An efficient and straightforward regularized Empirical Risk Minimization (ERM) algorithm is presented, along with a theoretical generalization result. Extensive experimental results demonstrate significant improvements over both uniform sampling and standard stratified sampling, which are considered industry standards.
The Kullback-Leibler distance, also known as the relative entropy, is computed between a probabilistic context-free grammar and a probabilistic finite automaton. A closed-form solution exists for the cross-entropy part of the Kullback-Leibler distance. The result has various applications in approximating probabilistic context-free grammars with probabilistic finite automata.
Face recognition and pose invariance are challenging aspects for most practical applications. This work focuses on recognizing faces using video sequences for training and recognition input in a realistic setup with varying lighting, pose, and user motion patterns. The novelty lies in combining a photometric model with a statistical model to handle extreme illumination changes, utilizing geodesically local appearance manifold structure for invariance to unseen head poses, and introducing a reillumination algorithm for robustness to face motion patterns in video. The automatic recognition system based on this method was evaluated on 171 individuals and over 1300 video sequences, achieving a nearly perfect recognition rate of over 99.7% across all three databases, surpassing state-of-the-art commercial software and methods from the literature.
Minimum Bayes-Risk (MBR) decoding is a statistical approach used in machine translation to minimize the expected loss of translation errors. This approach incorporates a hierarchy of loss functions that consider different levels of linguistic information, including word strings, word-to-word alignments from machine translation systems, and syntactic structures from parse-trees of source and target language sentences. The performance of MBR decoders was evaluated on a Chinese-to-English translation task, showing that MBR decoding can be effective in tuning statistical machine translation performance for specific loss functions.
This paper discusses the evaluation approaches used for Natural Language systems. Previous approaches have not considered evaluating systems in the context of their use, such as solving tasks that involve data retrieval, raising concerns about the validity of those approaches. A laboratory study using the Wizard of Oz technique was conducted to identify NL requirements for performing this task. The study evaluated the demands that task dialogues collected using this technique placed on a prototype Natural Language system. Three important requirements emerged from the task given to the subjects: operators specific to database access, complex contextual references, and references to the structure of the information source. The paper also explores how future Natural Language systems could meet these requirements.
We present results on addressee identification in four-participants face-to-face meetings using Bayesian Network and Naive Bayes classifiers. The study investigates the prediction of the addressee of a dialogue act based on gaze, utterance, and conversational context features. The classifiers achieve the best results when conversational context and utterance features are combined with the speaker's gaze information. However, there is little improvement observed when incorporating information about meeting context.
Towards deep analysis of compositional classes of paraphrases, we have examined a class-oriented framework for collecting paraphrase examples. Sentential paraphrases are collected for each paraphrase class separately through automatic candidate generation and manual judgment. Our preliminary experiments on building a paraphrase corpus have shown promising results, which we have evaluated based on cost-efficiency, exhaustiveness, and reliability.
The research focuses on evaluating the effectiveness of using automated evaluation techniques originally designed for assessing human language learners on machine translation systems. The experiment specifically looks at the intelligibility of machine translation output. Assessors were able to differentiate between native and non-native language essays in a short text. The experiment involved subjects evaluating extracts of translated newswire text to determine if they were expert human translations or machine translations. The results of the experiment and an analysis of the decision-making process will be presented.
This paper presents a machine learning approach to bare slice disambiguation in dialogue. We extract a set of heuristic principles from a corpus-based sample and formulate them as probabilistic Horn clauses. We then use the predicates of such clauses to create a set of domain independent features to annotate an input dataset, and run two different machine learning algorithms: SLIPPER, a rule-based learning algorithm, and TiMBL, a memory-based system. Both learners perform well, yielding similar success rates of approximately 90%. The results show that the features in terms of which we formulate our heuristic principles have significant predictive power, and that rules that closely resemble our Horn clauses can be learnt automatically from these features.
We propose a new evaluation criterion for word similarity measures, called meaning-entailing substitutability, which is suitable for semantic-oriented NLP applications. This criterion can be assessed independently of any specific application with a high level of human agreement. We examine the quality of distributional word feature vectors and their impact on word similarity results, introducing an objective measure for evaluating the quality of these feature vectors. Additionally, we present a novel feature weighting and selection function that generates superior feature vectors and enhances word similarity performance.
Reflections in image sequences consist of multiple layers superimposed over each other. This phenomenon poses a challenge for many image processing techniques that assume the presence of only a single layer at each examined site, such as motion estimation and object recognition. This study introduces an automated technique for detecting reflections in image sequences by analyzing the motion trajectories of feature points. The model represents reflections as regions containing two distinct layers moving over each other. A robust detector is developed by combining a set of weak detectors. The approach utilizes novel priors, generates sparse and dense detection maps, and achieves a high detection rate while addressing issues related to pathological motion and occlusion.
This paper discusses reconstructing the motion of a 3D articulated tree from 2D point correspondences with a temporal prior. Smooth motion has been encouraged using a trajectory basis. A dynamic programming approach is developed that scales linearly with the number of frames by leveraging the local nature of filter interactions. The extension to affine projection allows for reconstruction without the need to estimate cameras.
Topical blog post retrieval is the task of ranking blog posts with respect to their relevance for a given topic. To improve topical blog post retrieval, we incorporate textual credibility indicators in the retrieval process. We consider two groups of indicators: post level and blog level. Experiments on the TREC Blog track test set show that both groups of credibility indicators significantly improve retrieval effectiveness.
We focus on learning to predict moves in the board game of Go from expert game records. We generate a probability distribution over legal moves for professional play in a given position. This distribution has various applications in computer Go, such as functioning as a standalone Go player, a move selector, and a move sorter for game tree search, and a training tool for Go players. Our approach consists of two main components: a pattern extraction scheme for efficiently extracting patterns from expert game records and a Bayesian learning algorithm that learns a distribution over move values based on the local pattern context. The system is trained on 181,000 expert games and demonstrates excellent prediction performance, accurately predicting professional Go players' moves in 34% of test positions.
We present a novel approach for automatically acquiring English topic signatures. A topic signature is a set of words that tend to co-occur with a particular concept or word sense. Topic signatures can be useful in various Natural Language Processing (NLP) applications, such as Word Sense Disambiguation (WSD) and Text Summarisation. Our method leverages the lexicalisation of word senses in English and Chinese, as well as the abundance of Chinese text in corpora and on the Web. We evaluated the topic signatures in a WSD task using a second-order vector cooccurrence algorithm on standard WSD datasets, yielding promising results.
Joint matrix triangularization is a technique commonly used in signal processing and machine learning. It is used to estimate the joint eigenstructure of a set of matrices. The problem of approximate joint matrix triangularization arises when the matrices are jointly diagonalizable and real, but only noisy versions are available. Our main result provides a first-order upper bound on the distance between an approximate joint triangularizer of the observed noisy matrices and an exact joint triangularizer of the original matrices. Importantly, this bound depends solely on the observed matrices and the level of noise, without relying on specific optimization properties of the triangularizer. This represents a novel a posteriori bound for joint matrix decomposition, validated on synthetic data with known ground truth.
The psycholinguistic literature provides evidence for syntactic priming, the tendency to repeat structures. This paper describes a method for incorporating priming into an incremental probabilistic parser. Three models are compared, involving priming of rules between sentences, within sentences, and within coordinate structures. These models simulate the reading time advantage for parallel structures found in human data and also yield a small increase in overall parsing accuracy.
Learned confidence measures, outlier removal, and quality improvement are crucial in stereo vision. Acquiring training data can be time-consuming, involving manual interaction, active sensing devices, and synthetic scenes. To address this, we propose a new, flexible, and scalable approach for generating training data using stereo images. Our approach leverages different viewpoints to analyze contradictions and consistencies among multiple depth maps from the same stereo algorithm, allowing us to automatically generate a large amount of training data. In experiments, we demonstrate the effectiveness of our approach in enhancing the performance of three learned confidence measures on the KITTI2012 dataset by training them on a vast amount of automatically generated training data instead of limited laser ground truth data.
An important area of learning in autonomous agents is the ability to learn domain-specific models of actions to be used by planning systems. In this paper, we present methods by which an agent learns action models from its own experience and from its observation of a domain expert. These methods differ from previous work in the area in two ways: the use of an action model formalism which is better suited to the needs of a reactive agent, and successful implementation of noise-handling mechanisms. Training instances are generated from experience and observation, and a variant of GOLEM is used to learn action models from these instances. The integrated learning system has been experimentally validated in simulated construction and office domains.
FERRET is an interactive question-answering system. FERRET addresses the challenges of integrating automatic Q/A applications into real-world environments. FERRET utilizes a novel approach to Q/A known as predictive questioning. Predictive questioning attempts to identify the questions and answers that users need by analyzing how a user interacts with a system while gathering information related to a particular scenario.
An annotation scheme for scientific articles is introduced in this paper to enhance training resources for automatic abstracting systems. The scheme categorizes information based on rhetorical moves of argumentation. Experimental results show the stability, reproducibility, and usability of the scheme.
The automated segmentation of images into semantically meaningful parts requires shape information. Low-level feature analysis alone often fails to reach this goal. A novel method of shape constrained image segmentation is introduced, based on mixtures of feature distributions for color and texture, as well as probabilistic shape knowledge. The combined approach is formulated in the framework of Bayesian statistics to account for the robustness requirement in image understanding. Experimental evidence shows that semantically meaningful segments are inferred, even when image data alone gives rise to ambiguous segmentations.
The goal of this work is to enhance human-machine interactions in a natural language environment. Difficulties and mistakes can arise in conversations due to differences in beliefs, contexts, perceptions, backgrounds, or goals between the speaker and listener, leading to miscommunication. The focus is on identifying and addressing miscommunications, particularly reference problems. The paper presents a case study and techniques to prevent failures of reference, advocating for a less restrictive framework that allows the speaker flexibility in forming utterances and choosing how to convey them in conversation. It also introduces a new perspective on extensional reference.
"Combination methods are an effective way of improving system performance. This paper examines the benefits of system combination for unsupervised WSD. We investigate several voting- and arbiter-based combination strategies over a diverse pool of unsupervised WSD systems. Our combination methods rely on predominant senses which are derived automatically from raw text. Experiments using the SemCor and Senseval-3 data sets demonstrate that our ensembles yield significantly better results when compared with state-of-the-art."
The applicability of many current information extraction techniques is severely limited by the need for supervised training data. For certain field structured extraction tasks, such as classified advertisements and bibliographic citations, small amounts of prior knowledge can be used to learn effective models in a primarily unsupervised fashion. Hidden Markov models (HMMs) provide a suitable generative model for field structured text, but general unsupervised HMM learning fails to learn useful structure in either of our domains. However, one can dramatically improve the quality of the learned structure by exploiting simple prior knowledge of the desired solutions. In both domains, unsupervised methods can attain accuracies with 400 unlabeled examples comparable to those attained by supervised methods on 50 labeled examples, and semi-supervised methods can make good use of small amounts of labeled data.
This paper discusses a prototype natural language question answering system called Chat-80. Chat-80 is designed to be efficient and easily adaptable to various applications. The system is implemented in Prolog, a logic-based programming language. Using a logic-based grammar formalism called extraposition grammars, Chat-80 translates English questions into a subset of logic in Prolog. A planning algorithm then transforms the logical expression into efficient Prolog, similar to query optimization in a relational database. Finally, the Prolog form is executed to provide the answer.
Human action recognition from well-segmented 3D skeleton data has been intensively studied and attracting an increasing attention. Online action detection goes one step further and is more challenging, which identifies the action type and localizes the action positions on the fly from the untrimmed stream. In this paper, we study the problem of online action detection from the streaming skeleton data. We propose a multi-task end-to-end Joint Classification-Regression Recurrent Neural Network to better explore the action type and temporal localization information. By employing a joint classification and regression optimization objective, this network is capable of automatically localizing the start and end points of actions more accurately. Specifically, by leveraging the merits of the deep Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) subnetwork, the proposed model automatically captures the complex long-range temporal dynamics, which naturally avoids the typical sliding window design and ensures high computational efficiency. Furthermore, the subtask of regression optimization provides the ability to forecast the action prior to its occurrence. To evaluate our proposed model, we build a large streaming video dataset with annotations. Experimental results on our dataset and the public G3D dataset both demonstrate very promising performance of our scheme.
The task of machine translation evaluation is closely related to sentence-level semantic equivalence classification. This paper explores the use of standard MT evaluation methods such as BLEU, NIST, WER, and PER in building classifiers for predicting semantic equivalence and entailment. A novel classification method based on PER, which incorporates part of speech information of words in sentence matches and non-matches, is also introduced. Results indicate that MT evaluation techniques can provide valuable features for paraphrase classification and, to a lesser extent, entailment. The technique proposed in this study significantly improves paraphrase classification accuracy compared to other models tested in the experiments.
Visual object tracking is a numerical optimization problem involving an object model and a black-box measure of similarity with candidate targets. Local optimization is used during normal tracking conditions to track the local mode of the similarity measure in a parameter space of translation, rotation, and scale. However, when the object is occluded, local tracking may fail, especially when prediction techniques like the Kalman filter are not effective. To address tracking failures, object detection is treated as a global optimization problem and solved using Adaptive Simulated Annealing (ASA), a method that prevents getting stuck at local modes and is faster than exhaustive search. ASA stochastically samples the parameter space, unlike local deterministic search. Cluster analysis is applied to the sampled parameter space to redetect the object and update the local tracker. This hybrid local and global mode-seeking tracker is tested on challenging airborne videos with heavy occlusion and large camera motions, outperforming state-of-the-art trackers on the VIVID benchmark datasets.
Techniques for automatically training modules of a natural language generator have recently been proposed. A fundamental concern is whether the quality of utterances produced with trainable components can compete with hand-crafted template-based or rule-based approaches. In this paper, we experimentally evaluate a trainable sentence planner for a spoken dialogue system by eliciting subjective human judgments. To perform an exhaustive comparison, we also evaluate a hand-crafted template-based generation component, two rule-based sentence planners, and two baseline sentence planners. The results show that the trainable sentence planner performs better than the rule-based systems and the baselines, and as well as the hand-crafted system.
A new algorithm is proposed for novel view generation in one-to-one teleconferencing applications. The video streams acquired by two cameras placed on either side of a computer monitor are used. The proposed algorithm synthesizes images from a virtual camera in an arbitrary position to facilitate eye contact. The technique is based on an improved dynamic-programming stereo algorithm for efficient novel-view generation. The main contributions of this paper are a new type of three-plane graph for dense-stereo dynamic-programming that encourages correct occlusion labeling and a compact geometric derivation for novel-view synthesis by direct projection of the minimum-cost surface. Additionally, a novel algorithm for the temporal maintenance of a background model to enhance the rendering of occlusions and reduce temporal artifacts is presented, along with a cost aggregation algorithm that acts directly on the three-dimensional matching cost space. Examples are provided to demonstrate the robustness of the new algorithm to spatial and temporal artifacts for long stereo video streams, including the synthesis of cyclopean views of extended conversational sequences. Synthesis from a freely translating virtual camera is also demonstrated.
Manual acquisition of semantic constraints in broad domains is very expensive. An automatic scheme for collecting statistics on cooccurrence patterns in a large corpus is presented in this paper. These statistics reflect semantic constraints and are used to disambiguate anaphora references and syntactic ambiguities. The scheme gathers statistics on the output of other linguistic tools. An experiment was conducted to resolve references of the pronoun "it" in randomly selected sentences from the corpus. The results of the experiment demonstrate that the cooccurrence statistics indeed reflect the semantic constraints and provide a basis for a useful disambiguation tool.
We present a novel method for discovering parallel sentences in comparable and non-parallel corpora. We train a maximum entropy classifier that can determine whether a pair of sentences are translations of each other. Using this approach, we extract parallel data from large Chinese, Arabic, and English non-parallel newspaper corpora. The quality of the extracted data is evaluated by its impact on the performance of a state-of-the-art statistical machine translation system. It is demonstrated that a high-quality MT system can be developed from a small parallel corpus (100,000 words) by leveraging a large non-parallel corpus. This method is particularly beneficial for language pairs with limited available resources.
In this paper, we discuss a search procedure for statistical machine translation (MT) using dynamic programming (DP). We introduce a technique inspired by the DP solution to the traveling salesman problem to control word reordering between the source and target languages for an efficient search algorithm. A specific search restriction for translating from German to English is outlined. Experimental tests are conducted on the Verbmobil task (German-English, 8000-word vocabulary), a limited-domain spoken-language task.
LR-parsers are a functional implementation that is a generalization of the recursive descent parser. The time-complexity of the parser for non-LR grammars is cubic when memo-functions are used to store previous results. Memo-functions also aid in creating a compact representation of the parse forest. For LR grammars, the algorithm is closely related to the recursive ascent parsers discovered by Kruse-man Aretz and Roberts. Extended CF grammars, which include regular expressions on the right-hand side, can be parsed with a simple modification of the LR-parser for normal CF grammars.
This paper explores a theory of discourse structure that focuses on the role of purpose and processing in discourse. The discourse structure comprises three components: linguistic structure, intentional structure, and attentional state. The linguistic structure includes segments of the discourse that naturally group utterances. The intentional structure captures discourse-relevant purposes and relationships among them. The attentional state represents the focus of attention of participants as the discourse progresses, noting salient objects, properties, and relations. This theory explains discourse phenomena such as cue phrases, referring expressions, and interruptions. Examples of discourses illustrate the theory of attention, intention, and aggregation of utterances. Various properties of discourse are described, and explanations for the behavior of cue phrases, referring expressions, and interruptions are explored. This theory offers a framework for describing the processing of utterances in discourse, involving recognizing how utterances aggregate into segments, understanding intentions and relationships among intentions, and tracking discourse through attentional mechanisms. Recognition tasks in this processing description involve information from the discourse and participants' knowledge of the domain.
We examine the relationship between Tree Adjoining Grammars and Head Grammars. We briefly investigate the weak equivalence of the two formalisms. We then turn to a discussion comparing the linguistic expressiveness of the two formalisms.
We present a comprehensive explanation of sentence-level and text-level anaphora in the context of a dependency-based grammar model. The criteria for resolving anaphora within sentences are based on key principles from GB's binding theory. The criteria for text-level anaphora integration involve a modified version of a Grosz-Sidner-style focus model.
Coedition of a natural language text and its representation in an interlingual form is the most effective way to facilitate text revision across languages. UNL graphs are considered the most suitable option for this purpose. A prototype is currently in development where, in a basic sharing scenario, users interact directly with the text in their language (L0) and indirectly with the associated graph. Any modifications made to the graph are then processed by the UNL-L0 deconverter, and the results are displayed. If the outcome is satisfactory, any errors are likely attributed to the graph rather than the deconverter, and the graph is then sent to deconverters in other languages. Users may also have the option to view versions in other languages they are familiar with, allowing for visible and encouraging improvement sharing. By adding new versions with appropriate tags and attributes to the original multilingual document, collaborative work on a document becomes feasible without any loss of information. Internally, connections between elements of the text and the graph are established using readily available resources such as a LO-English or L0-UNL dictionary, a morphosyntactic parser for L0, and a canonical graph2tree transformation. The goal is to achieve the best correspondence between the "UNL-tree + L0" and the "MS-L0 structure" by minimizing any overlapping connections through the use of the dictionary and aligning the tree and selected trajectory. This research aims to integrate approaches from pivot MT, interactive MT, and multilingual text authoring.
The reality of analogies between words is refuted by no one. Computational linguists seem to be quite dubious about analogies between sentences. Experiments were conducted on a multilingual corpus to estimate the number of analogies among the sentences it contains. Translation should preserve meaning to test for similar meanings.
Our goal is to learn a Mahalanobis distance by minimizing a loss defined on the weighted sum of the precision at different ranks. Our core motivation is that minimizing a weighted rank loss is a natural criterion for many problems in computer vision such as person re-identification. We propose a novel metric learning formulation called Weighted Approximate Rank Component Analysis (WARCA). We then derive a scalable stochastic gradient descent algorithm for the resulting learning problem. We also derive an efficient non-linear extension of WARCA by using the kernel trick. Kernel space embedding decouples the training and prediction costs from the data dimension and enables us to plug in arbitrary distance measures which are more natural for the features. We also address a more general problem of matrix rank degeneration and non-isolated minima in the low-rank matrix optimization by using a new type of regularizer which approximately enforces the orthonormality of the learned matrix very efficiently. We validate this new method on nine standard person re-identification datasets including two large scale Market-1501 and CUHK03 datasets and show that we improve upon the current state-of-the-art methods on all of them.
In this paper, we discuss language model adaptation methods given a word list and a raw corpus. The general method in this situation is to segment the raw corpus automatically using a word list, correct the output sentences by hand, and build a model from the segmented corpus. Our proposal in this paper is to focus on correcting the positions where the words in the list appear by taking a word as a correction unit. This method allows us to directly capture the statistical behavior of specific words in the application. In the experiments, we used various methods for preparing a segmented corpus and compared the language models based on their speech recognition accuracies. The results demonstrated the advantages of our method.
Practical modeling problems often involve discrete data that can be represented as draws from multinomial or categorical distributions. Examples include nucleotides in a DNA sequence, children's names in a specific state and year, and text documents. These data sets typically exhibit some form of dependency, such as the correlation between nucleotides in a DNA sequence or the correlation between children's names from year to year. The typical Dirichlet-multinomial formulation does not naturally capture these dependencies. To address this, a logistic stick-breaking representation and recent advancements in Pólya-gamma augmentation are utilized to reformulate the multinomial distribution using latent variables with jointly Gaussian likelihoods. This approach enables the application of various Bayesian inference techniques for Gaussian models with minimal additional complexity.
MINPRAN is an operator that specializes in finding good fits in datasets with more than 50% outliers. It does not require a known error bound for the good data and assumes that bad data are uniformly distributed within the sensor's dynamic range. MINPRAN utilizes random sampling to search for the best fit and the number of inliers least likely to occur randomly. The time complexity of MINPRAN is O(N^2 + SN log N), where S represents the number of random samples and N is the number of data points. MINPRAN analytically distinguishes good fits from random data and accurately identifies inliers regardless of the true inliers' percentage. Experimental confirmation on synthetic data demonstrates that MINPRAN performs well compared to least median of squares. Additionally, MINPRAN has been successfully applied to complex range and intensity data in related work.
Metagrammatical formalisms combine context-free phrase structure rules and metarules to express generalizations about the syntax of natural languages. Unconstrained MPS grammars pose computational risks. Various proposals for constraining them are evaluated based on computational tractability and explanatory adequacy. None of the proposals meets both criteria, indicating the need for further research on alternative metagrammatical formalisms.
Tree-adjoining grammars (TAG) are known for their unique properties. However, applying TAGs beyond syntax, such as in semantic interpretation or automatic translation of natural language, poses a challenge. Synchronous TAGs have been introduced to establish correspondences between languages. This formalism aims to connect expressions in natural languages with their semantic representations in logical form language or translations in other languages. The goal is to expand the use of TAGs beyond syntax. The application of synchronous TAGs to concrete examples is discussed, with some computational issues briefly mentioned.
A model-based approach to on-line cursive handwriting analysis and recognition is presented and evaluated. The model considers on-line handwriting as a modulation of a simple cycloidal pen motion, described by two coupled oscillations with a constant linear drift along the line of the writing. By modulating the amplitudes and phase lags of the two oscillators, a general pen trajectory can be efficiently encoded. These parameters are then quantized into a small number of values without affecting the writing intelligibility. The procedure for estimating and quantizing these cycloidal motion parameters for arbitrary handwriting is outlined. The result is a discrete motor control representation of the continuous pen motion through the quantized levels of the model parameters. This motor control representation enables successful word spotting and matching of cursive scripts. The experiments conducted demonstrate the potential of this dynamic representation for complete cursive handwriting recognition.
In the Object Recognition task, there is a distinction between categorizing objects and estimating object pose. Categorization requires a view-invariant representation, while estimating pose requires a representation that can capture pose information across different object categories. Deep architectures have primarily focused on object category recognition, with deep learning methods achieving significant success in this area. However, object pose estimation using these approaches has not received as much attention. This study explores how Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) architectures can be adapted for simultaneous object recognition and pose estimation. The research delves into the layers of various CNN models, comparing them extensively to understand how the distributed representations within CNNs capture object pose information and how this differs from object category representations. The experiments conducted on two recent large and challenging multi-view datasets demonstrate superior performance compared to the current state-of-the-art methods.
In this paper, we present our recent work on harvesting English-Chinese bitexts of the laws of Hong Kong from the Web and aligning them to the subparagraph level using the numbering system in the legal text hierarchy. The resulting bilingual corpus consists of 10.4 million English words and 18.3 million Chinese characters, providing an authoritative and comprehensive text collection on the specific domain of HK laws. This corpus is valuable for empirical MT research and lays a foundation for further exploration and harvesting of English-Chinese bitexts from the Web.
Light fields are image-based representations that use densely sampled rays as a scene description. In this paper, we explore geometric structures of 3D lines in ray space for improving light field triangulation and stereo matching. The triangulation problem aims to fill in the ray space with continuous and non-overlapping simplices anchored at sampled points (rays). Such a triangulation provides a piecewise-linear interpolant useful for light field super-resolution. We show that the light field space is largely bi-linear due to 3D line segments in the scene, and direct triangulation of these bilinear subspaces leads to large errors. We instead present a simple but effective algorithm to first map bilinear subspaces to line constraints and then apply Constrained Delaunay Triangulation (CDT). Based on our analysis, we further develop a novel line-assisted graph-cut (LAGC) algorithm that effectively encodes 3D line constraints into light field stereo matching. Experiments on synthetic and real data show that both our triangulation and LAGC algorithms outperform state-of-the-art solutions in accuracy and visual quality.
This paper presents a phrase-based statistical machine translation method based on non-contiguous phrases. A method for producing such phrases from a word-aligned corpora is proposed. A statistical translation model is also presented that deals with such phrases, as well as a training method based on the maximization of translation accuracy measured with the NIST evaluation metric. Translations are produced by means of a beam-search decoder. Experimental results are presented to demonstrate how the proposed method allows for better generalization from the training data.
"GLOSSER is a program designed to support reading and learning in a foreign language. GLOSSER currently supports four language pairs: English-Bulgarian, English-Estonian, English-Hungarian, and French-Dutch. The program is operational on UNIX and Windows '95 platforms and has undergone a pilot user-study. A demonstration for Applied Natural Language Processing emphasizes components used in intelligent computer-assisted morphological analysis (ICALL), including disambiguated morphological analysis and lemmatized indexing for a bilingual corpus of word examples."
We present a new part-of-speech tagger that utilizes both preceding and following tag contexts through a dependency network representation. The tagger also incorporates a wide range of lexical features, including conditioning on multiple consecutive words, effectively utilizing priors in conditional loglinear models, and finely modeling unknown word features. As a result of these approaches, the tagger achieves an accuracy of 97.24% on the Penn Treebank WSJ.
Person re-identification is a challenging task due to factors such as pose, illumination, occlusion, and camera view. The pedestrian data forms highly-curved manifolds in the feature space. The distribution of the data is unknown, making geodesic distance comparison difficult. Current deep embedding methods use Euclidean distance for training and testing. Manifold learning methods suggest using Euclidean distance locally and considering the graphical relationship between samples to approximate geodesic distance. Selecting suitable positive training samples within a local range is crucial for training CNN embedding, especially with large intra-class variations. A novel moderate positive sample mining method is proposed to address the issue of large variation in person re-identification. Learning is enhanced through a metric weight constraint to improve generalization ability. Experimental results show the effectiveness of these strategies in learning robust deep metrics for person re-identification, with the deep model surpassing state-of-the-art methods on various benchmarks. This study may inspire new designs of deep models for person re-identification.
"Utterance Verification (UV) is a critical function of an Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) System. It deals with spontaneous speech, out-of-vocabulary (OOV) words, and acoustic noises. A new UV procedure is presented in this paper with Word Spotting and Noise Spotting capabilities. The procedure includes confidence tests based on acoustic measures and linguistic information. Experimental results from a real telephone application show a 50% reduction in recognition errors with a 12% rejection rate of correct utterances and a 1.5% rate of false acceptance."
A critical step in encoding sound for neuronal processing occurs when the analog pressure wave is coded into discrete nerve-action potentials. Recent pool models of the inner hair cell synapse do not reproduce the dead time period after an intense stimulus. Visual inspection and automatic speech recognition (ASR) were used to investigate an offset adaptation (OA) model proposed by Zhang et al. OA improved phase locking in the auditory nerve and raised ASR accuracy for features derived from auditory nerve fibers. OA is crucial for auditory processing by onset neurons in the auditory brainstem. Multi-layer perceptrons (MLPs) performed much better than standard Gaussian mixture models (GMMs) for both auditory features based on auditory nerve fibers and onset neurons. Similar results were previously obtained with Modulation-filtered SpectroGram (MSG) auditory features. Researchers working with novel features should consider trying MLPs.
Recent progress in computer vision has been driven by high-capacity models trained on large datasets. Creating large datasets with pixel-level labels has been costly due to the amount of human effort required. In this paper, we present an approach to rapidly creating pixel-accurate semantic label maps for images extracted from modern computer games.
We propose a novel step towards unsupervised segmentation of whole objects by combining hints of partial scene segmentation using soft and binary mattes. These mattes are implied by hypothesized object boundary fragments in the scene. Instead of aiming for a single best segmentation, we generate multiple segmentations of an image. This approach aligns with current methods for unsupervised object discovery from groups of images and allows for defining evaluation metrics based on accurate delineation of scene objects. Our method builds on recent advancements in spectral clustering, image matting, and boundary detection. It has been demonstrated qualitatively and quantitatively on a dataset of scenes and is suitable for ongoing work in unsupervised object discovery without prior knowledge.
Language resource quality is crucial in NLP. Many of the resources used are derived from data created by human beings out of an NLP context, especially regarding MT and reference translations. Automatic evaluations require high-quality data for comparing both automatic and human translations. It is widely recommended to validate these resources before use. This paper discusses the impact of using different-quality references on evaluation. Surprisingly, similar scores are obtained in many cases regardless of the quality. The limitations of automatic metrics used within MT are also discussed in this context.
This poster paper describes a full-scale two-level morphological description of Turkish word structures. The description has been implemented using the PC-KIMMO environment and is based on a root word lexicon of about 23,000 roots words. Turkish is an agglutinative language with word structures formed by productive affixations of derivational and inflectional suffixes to root words. Turkish has finite-state but rather complex morphotactics. Morphemes added to a root word or a stem can convert the word from a nominal to a verbal structure or vice-versa, or can create adverbial constructs. The surface realizations of morphological constructions are constrained and modified by a number of phonetic rules such as vowel harmony.
This paper focuses on generating the fundamental frequency (F0) contour of speech from a text input for text-to-speech synthesis. A statistical model describing the generation process of speech F0 contours, based on the discrete-time version of the Fujisaki model, has been introduced previously. One notable aspect of this model is its ability to derive an efficient algorithm using statistical methods to estimate the Fujisaki-model parameters from raw F0 contours. To link a sequence of Fujisaki-model parameters with a text input through statistical learning, this paper suggests expanding this model to a context-dependent one. Additionally, a parameter training algorithm for this model is proposed based on decision tree-based context clustering.
We propose a method to speed up the evaluation of object detection cascades by using a divide-and-conquer approach in the candidate regions space. This method requires fewer evaluations of classifier functions compared to the exhaustive procedure currently used for cascade evaluation, resulting in faster search. Additionally, we demonstrate how the efficient subwindow search (ESS) procedure can be integrated into our method's final stage. This integration allows our method to not only accelerate cascade evaluation but also efficiently perform branch-and-bound object detection using nonlinear quality functions, specifically kernel-ized support vector machines. Experiments on the PASCAL VOC 2006 dataset indicate a more than 50% acceleration compared to standard cascade evaluation.
Background modeling is an important component of many vision systems. Existing work in the area has mostly addressed scenes that consist of static or quasi-static structures. In this paper, we propose a new method for the modeling and subtraction of scenes with persistent dynamic behavior. Optical flow is computed and utilized as a feature in a higher dimensional space. Ambiguities in feature computation are addressed by using a data-dependent bandwidth for density estimation with kernels. Extensive experiments demonstrate the utility and performance of the proposed approach.
Information distillation is the process of extracting relevant information related to a given query from large, possibly multilingual, audio and textual document sources. In this paper, we discuss our method of using information extraction annotations to enhance document retrieval for distillation. We leverage the fact that some distillation queries can be linked to annotation elements used in the NIST Automatic Content Extraction (ACE) task. Our experiments demonstrate that utilizing ACE events to limit the document set retrieved by an information retrieval engine significantly enhances precision at various recall rates for different query templates.
This paper presents a novel representation for three-dimensional objects using affine-invariant image patches and their spatial relationships. Multi-view constraints associated with groups of patches are combined with a normalized representation of their appearance to guide matching and reconstruction. This allows the acquisition of true three-dimensional affine and Euclidean models from multiple images and their recognition in a single photograph taken from any viewpoint. The proposed approach eliminates the need for a separate segmentation stage and is applicable to cluttered scenes. Preliminary modeling and recognition results are provided.
Fast algorithms for nearest neighbor search have largely focused on distance. An approach for distance involves an explicit and exact distance-preserving embedding of points into 2. This can be efficiently combined with random-projection based methods for nearest neighbor search, such as locality-sensitive hashing or random projection trees. The correctness of the methodology is rigorously established, and experimentation using locality-sensitive hashing shows it is competitive with available alternatives.
